\description{
\code{mcnemar_test()} tests whether paired proportions have changed between
two dichotomous measurements. Use this for before/after comparisons of
categorical outcomes.

Think of it as:
\itemize{
\item A paired comparison test for binary (yes/no) data
\item The categorical equivalent of a paired t-test
\item Tests whether the proportion of "changers" is symmetric
}

The test tells you:
\itemize{
\item Whether paired proportions changed significantly
\item Both asymptotic and exact p-values for maximum reliability
\item The number of discordant pairs (who actually changed)
}
}
\details{
\subsection{Understanding the Results}{

\strong{P-value}: If p < 0.05, the paired proportions are significantly different
\itemize{
\item p < 0.001: Very strong evidence of change
\item p < 0.01: Strong evidence of change
\item p < 0.05: Moderate evidence of change
\item p >= 0.05: No significant change found
}

\strong{Exact vs Asymptotic}: The exact binomial p-value is more reliable for
small samples. For large samples, both p-values will be very similar.

\strong{Discordant Pairs}: Only pairs where the two measurements differ (b and c)
contribute to the test. If b approximately equals c, there is no evidence of
systematic change.
}

\subsection{When to Use This}{

Use McNemar's test when:
\itemize{
\item You have paired or matched binary data
\item You're comparing before/after proportions
\item Both variables must be dichotomous (exactly 2 levels)
}
}

\subsection{The McNemar Statistic}{

For a 2x2 table with discordant cells b and c:
\deqn{\chi^2 = \frac{(|b - c| - 1)^2}{b + c}}
(with continuity correction)

The exact test uses a binomial test on the discordant pairs.
}

\subsection{Relationship to Other Tests}{
\itemize{
\item For unpaired categorical data:
Use \code{\link{chi_square}()} instead
\item For paired ordinal/continuous data:
Use \code{\link{wilcoxon_test}()} instead
\item For paired data with more than 2 levels:
Consider the Bowker test of symmetry
}
}

